# De-Slop Pass

After AI-assisted implementation, run a focused cleanup to remove common AI-generated code artifacts. This is a separate pass from implementation — do not constrain generation, clean up afterwards.

## What to Remove

### Unnecessary Comments

```typescript
// BAD: Narrating what the code does
// Get the user from the database
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { id } });
// Check if user exists
if (!user) {
  // Return 404 if not found
  return NextResponse.json({ error: "Niet gevonden" }, { status: 404 });
}

// GOOD: Code speaks for itself, comment only explains non-obvious intent
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { id } });
if (!user) {
  return NextResponse.json({ error: "Niet gevonden" }, { status: 404 });
}
```

### Defensive Checks on Trusted Paths

```typescript
// BAD: TypeScript already guarantees this
if (typeof userId === "string" && userId.length > 0) {
  const user = await getUser(userId);
  if (user !== null && user !== undefined) {
    // ...
  }
}

// GOOD: Trust the type system
const user = await getUser(userId);
if (!user) return null;
```

### Tests That Test the Language/Framework

```typescript
// BAD: Testing that TypeScript types work
it("should accept a string parameter", () => {
  const result = formatName("test");
  expect(typeof result).toBe("string");
});

// BAD: Testing that arrays work
it("should return an array", () => {
  const result = getUsers();
  expect(Array.isArray(result)).toBe(true);
});

// GOOD: Test business logic and behavior
it("should format name as 'Voornaam A.' for display", () => {
  expect(formatName("Jan", "Jansen")).toBe("Jan J.");
});
```

### Over-Engineered Abstractions

- Factory patterns for a single implementation
- Abstract classes with only one concrete subclass
- Wrapper functions that just forward all arguments
- Configuration objects for something used exactly once

### Other Slop

- `console.log` statements (use Sentry logger)
- Commented-out code blocks
- Unused imports
- English strings in user-facing code (must be Dutch)
- Overly verbose error handling that obscures the actual logic
- `any` type casts added "to make it work"

## How to Run

After implementing a feature with AI assistance:

1. Review the diff: `git diff --stat`
2. For each changed file, scan for the patterns above
3. Remove slop while keeping all behavior-preserving logic
4. Run tests after cleanup to ensure nothing broke

## Key Principle

> Rather than adding negative instructions which constrain generation quality, add a separate de-slop pass. Two focused steps outperform one constrained step.
